{"id":"2205.02612","submitter":"Niels Lubbes","authors":"Georg Grasegger, Boulos El Hilany, Niels Lubbes","title":"Coupler curves of moving graphs and counting realizations of rigid\n  graphs","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AG math.CO math.MG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A calligraph is a graph that for almost all edge length assignments moves\nwith one degree of freedom in the plane, if we fix an edge and consider the\nvertices as revolute joints. The trajectory of a distinguished vertex of the\ncalligraph is called its coupler curve. To each calligraph we uniquely assign a\nvector consisting of three integers. This vector bounds the degrees and\ngeometric genera of irreducible components of the coupler curve. A graph, that\nup to rotations and translations admits finitely many, but at least two,\nrealizations into the plane for almost all edge length assignments, is a union\nof two calligraphs. We show that this number of realizations is equal to a\ncertain inner product of the vectors associated to these two calligraphs. As an\napplication we obtain an improved algorithm for counting numbers of\nrealizations, and by counting realizations we characterize invariants of\ncoupler curves.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 5 May 2022 12:48:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-05-06"}
